.TH VELVET 1 "2026-04-01" "velvet" "General Commands Manual"
.SH NAME
velvet \- a scriptable terminal multiplexer
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B vv
.RI [ options ]
.RI [ command ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B Velvet
is a fully scriptable terminal multiplexer which draws heavy inspiration from tmux and neovim.
Like tmux, velvet "multiplexes" IO between an arbitrary number of terminal applications in a single terminal session.
Like neovim, velvet supports scripting nearly all behavior through its lua API.

.PP
With no arguments,
.B vv
will start a new server and attach to it.
If a server is already running,
.B vv
will attach to the existing session.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI "\-S, \-\-socket " socket
Specify the socket path instead of the default.
.TP
.B \-h, \-\-help
Show usage information and exit.
.SH COMMANDS
.TP
.B attach
Attach to the server at the specified socket, or guess if omitted.
.TP
.B detach
Detach the current terminal from the session.
.TP
.BI "lua " "[code|\-]"
Execute
.I code
as a Lua chunk.
If
.I code
is omitted or
.B \-
is specified, read from stdin.
.TP
.B quit
Quit the velvet session, killing all windows.
.SH CONFIGURATION
.B velvet
will look for a configuration file at 
.B $HOME/.config/velvet/init.lua
at startup. If no configuration file is found, it will source the bundled default_config.lua
The recommended way to get started is to load the default config at the top of your own config file,
and add adjustments on top.
.SS Config example
.nf
-- prefix key configurable
require('velvet.default_config').setup({ prefix = "<C-x>" })
-- your config below
.SS LSP support
The lua API is fully annotated with EmmyLua style doc comments. I recommend
setting up a lua LSP and pointing it to the Velvet lua distribution to get full
autocompletion and inline documentation:
.TP
.B .luarc.json
.nf
{
  "workspace.library": ["<velvet_path>/lua"],
  "runtime": {
    "version": "Lua 5.5"
  }
}
.fi
.PP
.SS Reloading
You can reload your config by pressing
.B <prefix>R,
or programatically by calling
.B vv.api.reload()

Reloading wipes all lua state and loads your config, but windows are preserved.
This is convenient while tinkering with your config; it is almost never necessary to restart Velvet,
and changes are immediately visible.

To selectively preserve state during reload, see
.BR velvet-session-storage (3)
.SH KEYBINDINGS
.B Velvet
supports mapping any key sequence to a lua function. It follows similar syntax and conventions to neovim.
.SS Example Keybinds
.nf
local map = require('velvet.keymap').set
local spawn = vv.api.window_create_process
.fi
\-\- pressing Ctrl + Shift + F1 will open bash in the 
.B $HOME
directory.
.nf
map("<C-S-F1>",
  function() spawn({"bash"}, { working_directory = os.getenv("HOME") }) end)
.fi
\-\- Pressing Ctrl + X and then C will open
.B $SHELL
in a new window.
.nf
map("<C-x>c", function() spawn(os.getenv("SHELL")) end)
.fi

.SS Modifiers
.B Velvet
supports the following modifiers:
.TP
.B S 
Shift
.TP
.B M
Alt
.TP
.B T
Meta
.br
Velvet treats meta and alt interchangably.
.TP
.B D
Super
.br
Most likely intercepted by your OS or hosting terminal.
.br
Refer to your terminal's documentation to learn how to pass this through.
.TP
.B C
Control
.PP
Note that modifier support depends on the terminal hosting
.B Velvet. Super,
and combining
.B Shift
and
.B Control
requires the hosting terminal to implement the
.I Kitty Keyboard Protocol.
If the protocol is not available, Velvet falls back to basic modifier support.

For detailed information about the keymap module, see
.BR velvet-keymap (3)
.SH SCRIPTING
Since everything is just lua, it is fairly easy to script even moderately complex tasks via shell commands.
Useful patterns include sending code to the server via heredocs or shell redirection:
.SS Heredoc
.nf
-- Close all windows named 'zsh'
vv lua <<LUA
local windows = vv.api.get_windows()
for _, id in ipairs(windows) do
  local title = vv.api.window_get_title(id)
  if title and title:match("^zsh$") then vv.api.window_close(id) end
end
LUA
.SS Prepared scripts
vv lua < myscript.lua
.SS One-off commands
vv lua 'vv.options.theme.blue = "#0000ff"'
.SH ADVANCED USAGE
The C engine tries to make as few assumptions as possible; in a nutshell, it performs the following tasks:

1. Implements a VT220 compatible emulator, plus modern extensions,
.br
2. Dispatches system IO and timers on an event loop,
.br
3. Raises lua events when something happens (keyboard input, process output, etc.),
.br
4. Composites windows (based on Z index) and draws to the screen when buffer content changes,
.br
5. Provides a socket that clients can connect to.
.br

All other system behavior is defined in lua by interfacing with the low level api in the
.B vv.api
namespace.

For example, the core engine raises an event on key input. If the lua side does
not send that event to a window, it doesn't go anywhere. This makes it possible
to define your own keybind implementation.

As another example, the engine has no notion of a window border; the default
configuration creates borders by spawning four lightweight windows (window
objects with no backing process or pty), and setting their dimensions to [1x42]
and [22x1] to cover a [20x40] window. It then hooks up an event to update the
border positions whenever the attached window is moved or resized, and
registers themselves as child windows of the attached window so they are
automatically destroyed when the parent exits.

All that is to say, the system is extremely flexible and extensible; any task
performed by Velvet can be trivially scripted, such as sending mouse input and
keystrokes to a window.

The related pages attempt to thoroughly document the intended usage of each
provided default module at a high level, but the best way to explore what is
possible is to read the default config. (default_config.lua)

.SH SEE ALSO
.BR velvet-keymap (3)
.BR velvet-session-storage (3)
